>
  <p>
    When people say a septic repair "cost a fortune" or "was no big deal," they're often describing
    completely different jobs under the same word. A septic system is a chain of parts — the tank and
    its baffles, sometimes a pump, the pipes between them, a distribution box, and the drain field —
    and each can fail in its own way and at its own cost. Understanding that chain is the key to
    understanding why repair pricing swings so widely, and why a real number always follows a look at
    the system.
  </p>

  {/* Intended asset: /images/resources/septic-repair-cost-factors-hero.webp — see public/images/resources/README.md */}
